MissionCommands.Message: [Mattingly] Hello, Aquarius; Houston. How do you read?
Okay. Very good, Ken.

Okay. Let me take it from the top here. Just - there might be some overlap, but to make sure we're all on the same signal. We're starting off with a set of time line procedures that are going to give us - end up with the normal entry checklist. There will be some checklist changes into the book, but the bulk of what I have for you is the time line stuff.

And it starts at 6 hours and 30 minutes prior to EI and assumes that we're getting LM power to Main B in the Command Module. I think you already have the numbers for the LM PADs and the Command Module PADs; I mean the types of PADs we'll be giving you. And if you have a question on what they'll be doing or what they're for, I can go over those now or when we get through.
Okay. Yes, I'll make a little note there, and we'll discuss it when we get everything copied, huh?
All right. And the first item, then, after you get ready to start this checklist, is to install lithium hydroxide canisters and to stow ORDEAL. On panel 8, we want to turn the Floodlights to Fixed.
Okay. Wait a minute. You're going too fast, here. [Optional: Get some paper and write down the procedures. It will be available in-game too]
Okay. I'll tell you. I'll go line at a time and wait for your verification before I go on to the next one. I have panel 8, Floodlights, Fixed.
EI-6+30: Install LiOH canisters, stow ORDEAL, PNL 8 FLOOD - FIXED.

Okay. That's the panel 8 floodlights. Now we're going to take panel 5 and put the Floodlight rheostat to Flood and the LEB, that's panel 100, Floodlights are also going to Fixed. And the purpose of this is to balance up buses A and B.
PNL 5: INTERIOR LTS REHOSTAT TO FLOOD, LEB100 FLOOD - FIXED.
Okay. On panel 8: circuit breakers EMS, Main A and Main B, that's two, open.
PNL 8: EMS MNA & MNB (2) - OPEN
On panel 250: circuit breaker Battery A Power Entry and Postlanding, Closed.
PNL 250: CB BATT A ENTRY & POSTLANDING - CLOSED
Okay. The same for circuit breaker Battery B Power Entry and Postlanding.
PNL 250: CB BATT B ENTRY & POSTLANDING - CLOSED
Okay. And add Battery C Power Entry and Postlanding.
PNL 250: CB BATT C ENTRY & POSTLANDING - CLOSED
On panel 5: circuit breaker Bat Charge, Battery A Charge, Closed.
PNL 5: CB BATT CHRG BATT A CHRG - CLOSED
Okay. And the same for circuit breaker for Battery Charge, Bat B/Charge, Closed.
PNL 5: CB BATT CHRG BATT B CHRG - CLOSED
All right. Like to take Main Bus Ties, two of them, On and up. That's probably a verify.
PNL 5: MAIN BUS TIES (2) - ON (UP)
Circuit breaker Battery Relay Bus, Battery A and B, Closed.
BATT RELAY BUS BATT A & B - CLOSED
Circuit breaker EPS Sensor Signal, Main A and Main B, Closed.
EPS SENSOR SIGNAL MNA & MNB - CLOSED
On panel 275: circuit breaker Main A, Battery C, Closed.
PNL 275: MAIN A, BATT C - CLOSED
On panel 276: circuit breaker Instrumentation Power Control, 3 and 4, Open.
PNL 275: INST PWR CNTL CB 3 & 4 - OPEN
Okay. Panel 5: circuit breaker Essential Instrumentation Power, Main B, Closed.
PNL 5: CB ESS INST PWR MNB - CLOSED
We want to put the Primary and the Secondary Evaporator Water Control valves to Auto.
PNL 382: PRIM / SEC EVAP H2P CNTL VLV - AUTO (CW)
All right, the next little step after your water control valves is to perform the CSM RCS preheat. We'll do that on page E/1-5, steps 35 and 37.
CM RCS PREHEAT - E 1-5 STEP 35 & 37 [This is in the entry checklist]
Now back to panel 5: circuit breaker Caution and Warning, Main B, Closed.
PNL 5: CB C&W MNB - CLOSED
On panel 2: Caution and Warning Power to 1.
PNL 2: C&W PWR - 1
On panel 5: circuit breaker EPS Sensor Unit, DC Bus A and B, Closed.
PNL 5: EPS SENSOR UNIT DC BUS A & B - CLOSED
On panel 3: Main Bus A and B, go to Reset and leave it in the center.
MAIN BUS A&B - RESET/CENTER

Okay, now we're at EI minus 5 plus 05. And, as far as you're concerned, Jack, the Command Module is using this for information only. This will be the LM doing an Earth terminator AGS alignment; and at the time of 5 plus 05 is the time they'll be going ahead and releasing their ball. And this will be covered in the LM checklist; it'll be uplinked after this one. At EI minus 5, we perform midcourse number 7. Over.
EI-5+05: Earth Terminator AGS align, EI-5+00: MCC 7

At the completion of midcourse 7, the LM will maneuver to a separation attitude. And this attitude will be sent up on one of the PADs that you're going to get before all the sequence starts. And it'll be flown to the LM ball angles on that PAD.
EI-5+00: MCC 7; MANEUVER TO SEP ATTITUDE
At EI minus 4 plus 40, we want to perform page 1-6, step 39 of the entry checklist.
EI-4+40: PERFORM PYRO BAT CHECK STEP 39 E 1-6
The next is the Command Module RCS activation, and that's step 41 of page E/1-6.
PERFORM CM RCS ACTIVATION - step 41 on E/1-6
The next is at EI minus 4 plus 30. We want to verify that the LM is configured for Command Module RCS hotfire.
EI-4+30: LM CONFIGURED FOR CM RCS HOT FIRE
Now to panel 5: circuit breaker G&N IMU Heater, Main B, Closed.
PNL 5: G/N IMU HTR MNB - CLOSED
Panel 1: Rotation Control Power, Normal. That's two of them, to AC/DC.
PNL 1: ROT CNTL PWR NORMAL (2) - AC/DC
On panel 7: SCS, Logic Power 2/3, On.
PNL 7: SCS LOGIC PWR 2/3 - ON
Back to panel 2: RCS Command, On.
PNL 2: RCS COMMAND - ON
Now the Command Module RCS check per step 4 of page E/2-1.
CM RCS CHECK STEP 4 E/2-1
Okay, at this point, we want to lock the rotation hand controllers.
LOCK RHC'S
On panel 8: Sequential, Pyro Arm, two to Arm.
PNL 8: SECS PYRO (2) - ARM
Okay. Now, the next event is going to be the separation of the Service Module, and these are some LM steps, but so that you will know what is going on, I'll read them to you.

The LM will do a LM plus-X of one-half foot per second. Then you'll be hitting the CM SM Sep, On and up, on their command. As soon as we are free of the Service Module, the LM will do another LM minus-X for 0.5 feet per second. This is called the push-pull maneuver.
LM +X 0.5 FT/SEC; CM/SM SEP (2) - ON (UP); LM -X 0.5 FT/SEC
At the completion of that, we go back to panel 8, and it's Sequential, Pyro Arm, both of them, to Safe.
PNL 8: SECS PYRO (2) - SAFE
Okay. And following this, we take Sequential, Logic, two, to Off.
PNL 8: SECS LOGIC (2) - OFF

Then following this, the LM will pitch up to acquire the Moon - Excuse me, they're going to pitch up and acquire the Service Module and photograph, and they'll be using the ACA for rotations from now on.
LM PITCH UP TO ACQUIRE THE SM AND PHOTOGRAPH; USE LM ACA FOR ALL ROTATIONS

Okay, now we're down to EI minus 3 hours, or the next time-event, and the LM starts a maneuver to what we call the Moon-view attitude. This maneuver is designed to place the Command Module optics pointing with zero zero at the Moon, and it will be flown to on the LM ball angle.
EI-3+00: LM START MANEUVER TO "MOON VIEW" ATTITUDE
Okay, now we're going to panel 5, and it's circuit breaker G&N, Computer, Main B, Closed.
PNL 5: G/N COMPUTER MNB - CLOSED

And what we want to do is to put the computer to standby; if you come up with a 37 06, you'll have to do an Enter in order to get the code 62. If it's got 62 on it, you can do a Proceed until the DSKY blanks.
COMPUTER TO STBY: V37E 06E (PRO, DSKY BLANKS)
Now, we're at EI minus 2 plus 30; we're going to panel 5: circuit breaker Essential Instrumentation, Main A, Closed.
PNL 5: CB ESS INST MNA - CLOSED
Now circuit breaker G&N, IMU Heater, Main A, Closed.
PNL 5: CB IMU HTR MNA - CLOSED
CB LM Power-1 and -2, open.
PNL 5: CB LM PWR 1 & 2 - OPEN
CB G&N, Computer, Main A, Closed.
PNL 5: G/N COMPUTER MNA - CLOSED
I got it out of sequence. Would you put that Computer, Main A, ahead of LM Power?
That's CB G&N, Computer, Main A, Closed, goes before CB LM Power-1 and -2, Open.

That's correct. Jack, what we're doing is we've had the LM powering Main B, and we've had all these particular loads on it, and we're getting ready to secure LM power so we wanted to make sure that essential things like the computer, the platform, and all have dioded power supplies before we remove the LM power.
Now panel 275: circuit breaker Main B, Battery Bus B, Closed.
PNL 275: CB MNB BATT BUS B - CLOSED
Circuit breaker Inverter Power 1, 2, and 3, Closed.
PNL 275: CB INVERTER PWR 1, 2, 3 (4) - CLOSED
On panel 5: circuit breaker Battery Relay Bus, Battery A and B, Closed.
PNL 5: CB BATT RELAY BUS BATT A & B - CLOSED
Circuit breaker Inverter Control 1, 2, and 3, Closed.
PNL 5: CB INV CONTROL 1, 2 & 3 - CLOSED
On panel 3: AC Inverter 1, Main A.
PNL 3: AC INVERTER 1 - MNA
Now, AC Inverter 1, AC Bus 1, On.
PNL 3: AC INV AC BUS 1 - ON (UP)
And we're going to also put AC Inverter 1, AC Bus 2, On.
PNL 3: AC INV AC BUS 2 - ON (UP)
Back to panel 5. Circuit breaker EPS Sensor Signal, AC 1 and 2, Closed.
PNL 5: CB EPS SENSOR SIG AC 1 & 2 - CLOSED
Circuit breaker EPS Sensor Unit, AC 1 and 2, Closed.
PNL 5: CB EPS SENSOR UNIT AC 1 & 2 - CLOSED
And circuit breaker Caution/Warning, Main A, Closed.
PNL 5: C&W MNA - CLOSED
On panel 3: AC Inverter, AC Bus 1 and 2, Reset and back to the center.
PNL 3: AC INV AC BUS 1 & 2 - RESET (CENTER)
On panel 225: circuit breaker Flight Bus, Main A and Main B, Closed.
PNL 225: FLT BUS MNA & MNB - CLOSED
CB CTE, Main A and Main B, Closed.
CTE MNA & MNB - CLOSED
On panel 4: Telcom, Group 1, AC1.
TELECOM GROUP 1 - AC1
And Telcom, Group 2, to AC2.
TELECOM GROUP 2 - AC2
On panel 3: S-Band Normal, Transponder, to Primary.
PNL 3: S-BAND NORM XPONDER - PRIM
We want to take Power, SCE, to Normal, and Power, PMP, to Normal.
PNL 3: PWR SCE - NORM and PNL 3: PWR PMP - NORM
And Up Telemetry, Command Reset to Reset and then Normal.
PNL 3: UP TLM CMD RESET - RESET, then NORM
On panel 2: Up Telemetry, CMC, to Accept.
PNL 2: UP TM, CMC - ACCEPT
On panel 275: circuit breaker Flight/Postlanding, Main A and Main B, Closed.
PNL 275: CB FLT/POST LANDING MNA & MNB - CLOSED
And configure for Comm on panels 6, 9, and 10.
CONFIGURE FOR COMM ON PNL 6, 9 & 10
Panel 5: circuit breaker IMU, Main A and Main B, Closed.
PNL 5: CB IMU MNA & MNB - CLOSED
Circuit breaker Optics, Main A and Main B, Closed.
PNL 5: CB OPTICS MNA & MNB - CLOSED
CB G&N, Power, AC1 and AC2, Closed.
PNL 5: CB G&N PWR AC 1 & AC 2 - CLOSED
And the G&N Power switch to AC2.
PNL 5: G&N PWR SW - AC-2
Now we want to perform the CMC powerup per the CSM G&C checklist, G 2-2.
PERFORM CMC POWER UP - G 2-2
Perform the EMS check, step 32 of the entry book, page 1-4.
PERFORM EMS CHECK, STEP 32 ON E/1-4

Okay, now the ground is going to give you a P27 update, at EI minus 2 plus 15. That's a - that's a time that you need to be configured to accept up telemetry. And what they're going to give you on a P27 update will be a clock increment, a state vector; they'll give you a Verb 66; they'll give you two REFSMMATs, there'll be a actual and a preferred; and the entry target load.
EI-2+15: RECEIVE CLOCK INCR, STATE VEC, 2 REFSMMATS: ACTUAL AND PREFERRED, ENTRY TARGET, V66
IMU powerup according to the G&C checklist, G/2-1.
PERFORM IMU POWER UP - G/2-1
And while you are there, you can do the optics powerup on G/2-3.
PERFORM OPTICS POWER UP - G 2-3
On panel 229: circuit breaker Timers, Main A, Closed.
PNL 229: CB TIMERS MNA - CLOSED
That's correct. And the next thing you will do will be to set the mission timer and what we've done is to only turn on the mission timer on the MDC.
SET MISSION TIMER
Okay. Now, we are getting ready to start the alignment sequence, and are you familiar with the general sequence of events we're going to use, Jack?

How do you mean? We are going to make an alignment on the Moon and on the Sun; other than that - I didn't get any - I wasn't on the headset when the general information was passed up, so if there was any more than that, I didn't get it.

Okay. Basically, that is correct. Let me just run through it hand-waving type for a minute, and then I'll read you the steps. I think it will make more sense. The scheme is that the LM can fly to a set of ball angles that will point your optics at the Moon.

Now, at any time, in any attitude that we happen to be at, if you can look in the telescope and recognize star patterns sufficient that you believe you can make an alignment all on your own, that's the place we'd like to break off and let you go ahead and take over with your own alignment.

If you need to go on, we'll maneuver, take a look at the Moon, we'll take a mark there, and then we'll maneuver with the LM/FDAI angles again and take a look at the Sun, and get yourself another mark on the Sun and that will complete the alignment.

Now, the alignment scheme is that we are going to give you a set of angles that you can coarse align the ball through when the LM is pointing you at the Moon. Now, this set of angles will agree with the REFSMMAT that you have in as a nominal REFSMMAT in your CMC.

You can coarse align to that, set a drift flag and REFSMMAT flag, and you'll have a good platform and we'll be within a couple of degrees of a good alignment. And, if we have to, we could break off at this point and go ahead with an entry

However, in an attempt to get a good platform, we are going to have you then do a P52 option 1, and what you are going to find in the option 1 slots is the entry REFSMMAT. You'll come up with the Noun 22 values, and we intend to go ahead and coarse align the ball to the entry REFSMMAT attitude, and then we'll go ahead and take marks through a normal P52 sequence.
Okay. Well, let me ask a question. The LM maneuvers to a set of Moon-viewing angles. Okay, at this time, I am going to do a P52, is that right? With the planet option?

The first thing we are going to do is to coarse align the platform and get it inertial, based on the REFSMMAT that you have in the present slot inside the CMC. We'll then go - and do a P52, option 4 - Correction, option 1.
RECEIVE MNVR ATTITUDE FOR LM, COARS ALIGN, FINE ALIGN
[Okay. So that gives us a good platform.] Now the LM will maneuver to the jettison attitude
LM MANEUVER TO JETTISON ATTITUDE
Okay, and then the LM will go to a Max dead band attitude hold in the jettison attitude.
LM MAX DB, ATT HOLD
The next thing we'll do is to continue to powerup procedures. Panel 275. Have a circuit breaker Main A, Bat Bus A, Closed.
PNL 275: CB MAIN A BATT BUS A - CLOSED
And circuit breaker Main B, Bat C, Closed.
PNL 275: CB MAIN B BATT C - CLOSED
Now we're up to EI minus 1 plus 30. And at this time, we're going to proceed with the closeout and hatch installation.
EI-1+30: PROCEED WITH CLOSEOUT & HATCH INSTALLATION
Okay. Now let me give you some plumbing switches here. Let's take the Surge Tank Oxygen valve to On.
SURGE TANK - ON
Take the Main Regs, two, Open.
MAIN REGS (2) - OPEN
And the Water And Glycol Tank Pressure, the Pressure valve and the Relief valve to Both.
WATER AND GLYCOL TANK PRESSURE & RELIEF - BOTH
And Emergency Cabin Pressure valve to Both.
EMER CABIN REGS - BOTH
Suit Demand Regs to Both.
SUIT DEMAND REGS - BOTH
Okay, now we're going to panel 5: circuit breaker ECS Transducers, Pressure Group 1 and 2, Main A and Main B. That's four circuit breakers, Closed.
ECS TRANSDUCERS PRESS GROUP 1 & 2 MNA & MNB - CLOSED
Okay, now. Circuit breaker ECS Transducer, Temperature, Main A and Main B, that's two of them, Closed.
ECS TRANSDUCERS TEMP MNA & MNB - CLOSED
On panel 4: Primary ECS Glycol Pumps, one, to AC 1.
ECS GLYCOL PUMPS 1 - AC-1
That's correct. Okay, then we'll finish going back to the tunnel vent, and verify the LM/CM Delta-P and make sure it's been holding pressure.
VERIFY TUNNEL & LM/CM DELTA-P, more procedures later
The next thing I want to read off is the EI minus 1 plus 20. We'll go to panel 7: BMAG number 1 Power to Warm Up.
EI-1+20: PNL 7: BMAG NO. 1 PWR - WARMUP
Then at EI minus 1 plus 10, we'll perform SCS powerup per checklist, page G/2-4.
EI-1+10: PERFORM SCS POWER UP - G/2-4
Okay, on panel 4: Suit Compressor Number 2 to AC1.
PNL 4: SUIT COMPRESSOR 2 - AC-1
Spacecraft Control to SCS.
S/C CONTROL - SCS
And your Manual Attitude switches, as you desire. We're coming up on jettison of the LM, so that's just like separation.
MAN ATT SWITCHES - AS DESIRED
And we'll do a GDC align.
PERFORM GDC ALIGN
Rotation Control Power, Direct, 1 and 2, Main A/Main B.
ROT CNTL PWR DIRECT 1 & 2 - MNA/MNB
Okay, at EI minus 1 hour, we're going to be doing the LM jettison; so just prior to that, we want to do a P47.
All right, after we've done that, we want to get panel 8, Sequential, Pyro Arm, two of them, On.
SECS PYRO ARM (2) - UP/ON
All right; the next thing is CSM/LM Final Sep, two of them, On, up.
CSM/LM FINAL SEP (2) - UP/ON
Now we're going back to panel 8, and it's Sequential, Pyro Arm, two of them, to Safe.
SECS PYRO ARM (2) - SAFE
That's correct, and go back to P00.
GO BACK TO P00
And now it's time to configure for single ring.
CONFIGURE FOR SINGLE RING RCS

That's right, and since you're still an hour from EI, I guess it wouldn't hurt to use Minimum Impulse or something like that rather than the DAP, at least not until you get closer down. We'll have the DAP loads for you later. Okay. And as soon as you've gotten yourself all set up with a good control mode, you want to maneuver to the entry attitude.
MANEUVER TO ENTRY ATTITUDE
And we show EI minus 55, which really means when you get to the entry attitude, we have a sextant star check for you. And that will be on the PAD.
SEXTANT STAR CHECK
Turn the Optics Power Off and stow the optics.
OPTICS PWR OFF & STOW OPTICS
The next thing we'll do is to initialize the EMS and that's on entry checklist page 2-1, step number 2.
INITIALIZE EMS STEP 2 E/2-1
Now we're coming up on EI minus 45 minutes, and we'll give you an entry PAD and a final state vector.
ENTRY PAD & STATE VECTOR
Now we're going to perform what we call the Moon check.
MANEUVER TO "MOON CHECK" ATTITUDE
Okay, the next item on the check - checklist here is an EI minus 40; we're going to panel 7, and it's BMAG Number 2 Power to Warm Up.
BMAG NO.2 PWR - WARMUP
Now, I'd like to verify the Surge Tank and Repress Packages are On.
VERIFY SURGE TANK & REPRESS PKG ON
On panel 5: circuit breaker Environmental - Control System; Waste Water/Urine Dump Heater, two of them, Closed.
CB ECS CONT SYS WASTE WATER/URINE DUCT HTRS (2) - CLOSED
Suit Compressor number 2 to Off.
SUIT COMPRESSOR 2 - OFF
All right. Now we're at EI minus 30. Sequential, Logic, that's two of them, to On, up.
SECS LOGIC (2) - ON (UP)
Panel 7: the BMAG number 2 Power to On.
BMAG NO 2 PWR - ON
And FDAI Power to Both.
FDAI PWR - BOTH
And we want to activate the primary evaporator.
ACTIVATE PRIMARY EVAPORATOR
Okay, activate the primary evaporator. All this time, Ken, what we've been getting our cooling? Right now, I think we have the radiators at Pull To Bypass.

That's correct. We started out that way, and we turned the glycol pumps on, and we're just circulating it internally. And we're counting on the Command Module being a heat sink; it's pretty cold soaked, and it looks like this is good enough. You got some relatively low heat loads and we'll keep watching the temps, and if we need it, why we'll start the evaporator early.
Okay, that sounds good.
Do you believe it's cold up there?
Yes, and we used to call the Command Module the bedroom and it's now the refrigerator.
Okay, just don't call it the freezer. Okay. At about EI minus 19, we get back into the standard entry checklist on page 2-2, where it starts with P61.
GO TO ENTRY CHECKLIST E/2-2 (P61)
Okay, Jack. Now that's the - those are the timeline notes I had for you.

Hate to tell you this, but I also have a couple of corrections to make to the entry checklist. They aren't corrections, they just are pieces of the entry checklist which will correspond to what I've written - already read to you. And I'm ready to go on that whenever you are.

Okay, real fine. And I've got the entry checklist out and I'm ready to copy; just give me the page. [Follow the comments using the Apollo 13, CSM Entry Checklist available in the Flight Documents -> Apollo 13, CSM Entry Checklist]
Jack, you're starting to sound like an LMP.
I think I'm probably the only CMP that's ever witnessed an - a LM burn from inside the LM in - in space flight.
I hope it stays that way. Okay, Jack, we're starting on page 1-1.

Okay, down in the middle of the page on line 9, we're just going to strike out the "Activate VHF for Comm checks," and line 10, "Verify the DSE." We're going to leave the DSE Off, and that's to save power, as is the VHF activation.
Okay.
Okay, on page 1-2. At minus 2 hours, there's a title "Logic sequence" check; and we're deleting that entire sequence; that's included in what I read up to you.
Okay, delete the logic sequence check at minus 2 hours there.
That's correct. And delete lines 23, 24, and 25. That means a maneuver to Supercirc entry attitude. Everything below that is deleted.
Okay. Delete lines 23 through 28.
That's correct. You got ahead of me. All right, on line 29 on page 1-3, we're going to put in a time of minus 00:55. That's the time we gave you for the boresight check.
Okay
Okay, on the top of page 1-4; where it said "1 hour and 15 minutes" next to line 32, we're going to change that to "Minus 2 hours and 30 minutes".
Okay, minus 02:30 opposite item 32.

Okay, down at the bottom of the EMS entry check right there where we are, the bottom line now reads, "EMS Mode to Standby." Well, just above that - like to remind you to put a remark, "Do not initialize the range to go."

This is because you're going to come into the EMS entry check, you're going to run through all these things; then we're going to remove power from the EMS. And just didn't want you to get ahead of yourself and initialize the entry parameters, because you'll lose them when we power up.
Okay.
And, after we go EMS Mode to Standby, like for you to add "Circuit breaker EMS, two, to Open."
Okay, "CB EMS, two, to Open".

Okay. On the top of the next page where it says "Secondary water EVAP," just keep in mind we don't plan to use the secondary evaporators unless the primary fails. On line 35 on page 1-5, next to "Command Module RCS preheat," the time is now "Minus 06:30."
Okay, "minus 06:30".
All right, still on page 1-5, line 37; the time is now "Minus 06:10."
Got that.

And now let's go to page 1-6. And about one-third of the way down, it shows "Panel 275 CB Main A, Bat C, Closed," we want to strike off that line, the next two lines, and we're going to strike out "Main A, Bat C, Closed; Main B, Bat C, Closed;" and "DC Indicator, Main B."
Okay. After that step on panel 275, strike out "CB Main A, Bat C; CB Main B, Bat C"; and "DC Indicators to Main B".
That's correct. Now under panel 8, it tells you to "Close all circuit breakers except," and I have four additions. The first one is CB Service Module RCS Heaters, Quad Charlie, Main B, open.
Service Module RCS Heaters, Quad Charlie, Main Baker, open.
Okay. And the same thing for Service Module RCS Heater, Quad Delta, Main A, open.
Service Module RCS Heaters, Quad Delta, Main A, open.
That's correct. And Circuit breaker EMS, that's two of them, open.
CB EMS, two, to open.
All right. And the last is the circuit breakers for SPS GAGING, four of them, open.
SPS GAGING, four to open.
And let's go back to page 1-6, line 41. Let's put in a time "Minus 04:40".
Minus 04:40.
On page 2-1, line number 2, put in a time of "Minus 55 minutes".
Okay, minus 55 minutes.
Okay. And the first thing you want to do under "EMS initialization," is circuit breakers EMS, that's two of them, to Close.
Okay. CB EMS, two, to Close.
All right. Line 4 or step 4, where it shows "CM RCS check." That occurs at minus 04:30.
Okay. Minus 04:30.

All right. Under "CM RCS checks," the fourth line down says "Manual Attitude, three, to Minimum Impulse." We'll have to use "Accel Command" and the reason for that, Jack, is we don't have the SPS powered up so there's no minimum impulse generator.
Okay. Manual Attitude, three, to Accel Command.
That's correct. And on the same page 2-1, strike out the last three lines, starting with "RCS transfer to Service Module."
Right. The last three lines are scratched out. We ain't got one of those things.
Okay, let's flip to page 2-2 and strike out the first two lines.
Okay.
Now, we're - right below that, it says "Separation checklist." So we're going to just delete that whole thing; it's included in the notes I gave you.
Okay. It's included in the notations.
Okay. And at the bottom of the page, step number 1. That will be at EI minus 19 minutes, and we're off and running through a normal sequence of events.
Okay. That sounds good. Ken, I guess if you've read this thing - Is it a comfortable time line? Any areas where you had problems with?

Jack, it is very comfortable. We've run it several times now and, in fact, it's being run right now, again. And we've run it both here at Houston and at the Cape. The only place where you might find that you need to stay ahead of things is during the platform-alignment period, when you're getting ready to close out the LM.

And then once you get into the Command Module and jettison the LM, why you're back on a very comfortable time. And, of course, we'll be watching and anything we can do, like keeping track of time for you, we'll remind you of that as we go along.
Hey, that would be good - that would be good, Ken.
Let's look at the G&C book.
Okay. Ready to copy. [Optional: Follow the comments using the Apollo 13, CSM G&C Checklist]
Let's go to page 2-1. [This is page 42 in the Apollo 13, CSM G&C Checklist]

Okay, Jack. The second line under "IMU powerup" says "FDAI Power to Both," and we're going to make that a "1." The reason we're doing that is, again, to conserve power. There's no reason to drive the second FDAI before we get that information to put on it.
Okay. "FDAI Power to 1".
All right. And the last one I have for you is on page 2-4.
Okay. Go ahead. [Press READY to proceed]

Okay. Under the SCS powerup, the first line says "Auto RCS Select, 16, to Off." Okay. You can just delete that part. On the fifth line, it says "Circuit breaker SCS Logic Power," that's really "Logic Bus, four of them, to Closed." The Delta-V CG is not important since we are not burning the engine.

The "Signal Conditioner/Driver Bias Power" lists "Two to AC 1." We are going to make that just one of them; make it "Signal Condition/Driver Bias Power, one, to AC 1." The "BMAG Power," which is the third line from the bottom, says "BMAG Power, two, On;" we are going to make that just one.
We'll bring up number 1, and we'll make "FDAI Power, number 1" and the last line "Auto RCS Select, 16, enable," you can strike that off and replace it with "BMAG Mode, three of them, to Rate 1."

Okay. Delete "Auto RCS Select, 16, Off." Change "CB Logic Power" to "Logic Thrust Power - CBS CS Logic Thrust, four, to Closed." Delete "Delta-V CG," coming down here "Signal Conditioner/Driver Bias Power, one, AC 1; BMAG Power, 1, to On," and it's the number 1 BMAG. "FDAI Power to 1; BMAG Mode, three, to Rate 1," deleting the "Auto RCS Select, 16, to enable".
That's correct. You've got them all, Jack. Very good. Thank you.
Thank you. This does it, huh?
Yes, sir.

Okay, Jack. It looks like we've closed up the loose ends here. Amazingly enough, out of all that stuff, it looks like we only generated one question on the floor, and we'll research that one. We'll even let you guess what it might have been. If you have any questions, after you mull it over, why, we're always available. Just ask us what you're thinking about.

Okay. That's what we're going to do. We're going to wait until the LM people get theirs, and then we're going to discuss it and coordinate things here, and make sure that - that we don't have any interface problems. And, if we have any more questions, we'll be coming back at you.
We did run the thing integrated, so we think we've got all the little surprises ironed out for you.
I hope so because tomorrow is examination time.
Roger.
Ken, this is Jim.
Yes, sir.
Appreciate the work you've done, and Jack says that it's going to be hard to beat his record about saving SM RCS fuel all the way there and back.
I can't do much about that. Some people will do anything to set a record.
[Brand] Hey, Jack. We'll give you this battery charging backout procedure, and then Deke says you ought to get some sleep. You're going to need it tomorrow.
Okay. I'm ready to copy the backout procedure. [These will be executed immedeately]

Panel 3: Battery Charge, Off, next AC Inverter, Inverter 2 Off: Panel 5: Main Bus Tie Bat B/C to Bat B/C. Huh? Yes, it's up - the up position. Panel 250: circuit breaker, Bat A Power Entry/Postlanding to open; circuit breaker, Bat B Power Entry/Postlanding, open, Panel 5: CB Battery Charger Bat B Charge, open.
Now, that gets you back to the place where you can back out of the - the big battery charging procedure, which you have.
Yes, I do, Vance.
We request that you go ahead and finish out the backout completely until you get to square 1. Over.
Houston, Aquarius.
Go ahead, Jim.
Do you have any more updates for us?
We've still got a LM update, but we strongly recommend that you and Jack work as hard as you can sleeping for about the next 5 hours. Fred can handle it.
Okay. That's what we'll do. We'll put Fred on watch here, and Jack and I will take it easy, and if Fred copies the LM update, well, then we'll all start from fresh in the morning.
You bet.
[This completes the mission, the journey continues in the next]

Title: MISSION 21 - CM PROCEDURES
Description: The crew will finally receive the entry procedures.
BriefingText:
Primary objectives:
 to perform selenological inspection, survey, and sampling of
materials in a preselected region of the Fra Mauro formation;
 to deploy and activate an Apollo lunar surface experiments package;
 to further develop human capability to work in the lunar environment; and
 to obtain photographs of candidate exploration sites.

You can find the documnets needed here:https://www.nasa.gov/history/afj/ap13fj/a13-documents.html
